"1404":"1404","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1376":"1376","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","1395":"1395","about 1376":"about 1376","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","about 1374":"about 1374","1306":"1306","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Kinross-shire, Scotland":"Kinross-shire, Scotland","Portmoak, Kinross-shire, Scotland":"Portmoak, Kinross-shire, Scotland","Arnot, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Arnot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Arnott  .","German: variant of   Arnold  . This surname is very rare in Germany. In North America, it may also be an altered form of the variant <b>Arnodt</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Arnott","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a place called Arnot in Portmoak, Kinross.","Scottish and English: variant of   Arnold  .","English: variant of   Arnett  ."]},{"name":"Jarnot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse.","Polish: from the personal name <i>Jarnot</i>, an adaptation of German   Arnot  . It occurs mainly in western part of Greater Poland and on the borderland of Silesia and Lesser Poland (the areas of old German settlement in Poland).","French: variant of   Garneau  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>George</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Henry Arnot was born in 1330, in Portmoak, Kinross-shire, Scotland as the son of David 'The Devil' Arnot and Margery De Fife. He had at least 3 sons with Margaret Oliphant. He died in 1404, in his hometown, at the age of 74."},"et":{"1330–1404":"1330–1404","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1360–1413":"1360–1413","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1306–1395":"1306–1395","–Female":"Surnud","1404":"1404","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1376":"1376","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","1395":"1395","about 1376":"umbes 1376","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","about 1374":"umbes 1374","1306":"1306","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kinross-shire, Scotland":"Kinross-shire, Scotland","Portmoak, Kinross-shire, Scotland":"Portmoak, Ki